The song was released along with a music video shot in one-take with special appearances from pop rock band Body Type.

body.plain:
In “Pressure to Party,” Julia Jacklin rails against the societal convention and expectations of how we should feel after a failed relationship.

The song was released along with a music video shot in one-take with special appearances from pop rock band Body Type.

annotations: I would run, shoes off, straight back to you
Jacklin associates drinking with returning to unhealthy patterns. Despite breaking up with this person, she would run right back to them barefoot, regardless of knowing how bad they were for her

Meeting a stranger, touching his face
 I don’t want anyone to ever take your place

After a breakup, it’s hard to not compare every sexual/romantic encounter to your ex for a while, and there can also be a guilt with “moving on” and a feeling that you are replacing them with someone else

Pressure to not let the inside of my mind
 Spill onto the floor for our friends to find it
When you are drunk and partying, sometimes you share personal things you wouldn’t have shared while sober

Try to love again soon
 Try to love again soon
 Try to love again soon

Jacklin uses anaphora to emphasize the journey towards recovery that she’s going on. She feels the need to consistently diminish the pressure of other people in her emotional and romantic affairs. This gives voice to her constant pleads of isolation and self determination. It highlights how much she needs to push away outside forces as well as how these prying forces will not let up on her.
Before you find another heart where you belong

Jacklin dives into the societal pressure and myth of moving on before your ex does. She wants to be able to be alone to contemplate the effects of her breakup and take time to understand her emotional position in her romantic life. However, she knows that if she doesn’t move on before them, they will seem like the “winner” of the breakup. This also highlights how she still wants to be with them and it pains her to think of them with someone else.
Out on the dance floor with my body back

Autonomy over body is a consistent theme throughout Crushing, of which the first track is entitled “Body.”

In the following song, “Don’t Know How to Keep Loving You,” she sings that “I know your body now, and you know mine.” By saying that she feels pressure to go out dancing with “[her] body back,” she feels pressure to reclaim herself fully from her relationship.
I know where you live, I used to live there too

Here, Jacklin suggests that she “used to live there too” meaning she spent a lot of time at her ex’s place, either having lived with this person at some point, or spending so much time there that she essentially lived there too.

On a metaphorical level, Jacklin is saying that she could run back to where ‘[she] used to live", describing an emotional place in her life when she is connected with her former partner. He still lives in that emotional place, and she could run back to him.

description.plain:
“Don’t Know How to Keep Loving You” sees Jacklin reluctantly falling out of love with a long-term partner.

In a DIY Magazine interview, Jacklin said this of the song:
“I wrote this basically staring out the window one day in the tour van. I have always loved Fiona Apple’s ‘Not About Love’ and this is in that vein thematically I think. There’s not heaps of songs out there that cover the sadness of falling out of love, how powerless it can make you feel and then knowing you need to leave. That character doesn’t get as much sympathy as the one who has been left, so it’s a harder perspective to write from.”

A music video was released on October 15, 2019.

annotations:
What if I cleaned up? What if I worked on my skin?
 I could scrub until I am red, hot, weak, and thin
 Too tired to run away

With these lyrics, the narrator expresses a desire to scrub herself raw of all desire for something new. She connects her desire to leave, or even her lack of care for her lover, with a lack of cleanliness.
Into the darkness, or is it the light

This stark contrast between ‘darkness’ and ‘light’ serves to reinforce Julia’s sense of confusion. Usually the ‘light’ would be the certain, one true path to take, but confusing it with the ‘darkness’ only goes to show her lack of direction in this situation. The waters are murky, and she is unable to tell one truth from another.
We put so many things between these walls

Could be taken literally, that they live together and, as often happens, collect too much stuff as they settle.

It could also be interpreted metaphorically, in that so much of their relationship took place in their home, which now seems dull compared to the early passion and excitement of their relationship.

And every gift you buy me, I know what’s inside
 What do I do now? There’s nothing left to find

The spark in their relationship has begun to fade. There is not much space for surprises because she just knows them so well that her partner doesn’t invigorate her at all now or as much as they used to. She doesn’t feel it all when they kiss and she doesn’t want them as much as before.
I just wanna keep loving you
Julia doesn’t know how to keep loving them, but she wants to. There’s a sense of desperation to hold on to the good feelings referenced earlier in the song.
But you know my body now and I know yours

Awareness, recognition, and autonomy of her body is a consistent theme of Jacklin’s sophomore album, Crushing, of which the first track is “Body.” She states in the first song that “I guess it’s just my life and it’s just my body.”

Here, her line of “but you know my body know, and I know yours” continues the theme of recognizing our her body is known by her partner.

Finally, in “Pressure to Party” Jacklin describes the “Pressure to feel fine after the fact, Out on the dance floor with my body back,” referencing back to this line and reclaiming the autonomy of her body after leaving a relationship where her body was known not just by her, but her partner as well.

annotations:
Little sirens singing their songs
 Where have the babies gone?

children’s recitals are adorable, and arguably in this case can be weaponized to draw people into the unknown, like a siren.

she wonders where the innocent crying babies have gone, and how they turned into weapons for recruitment

The line up, the quiet
 The bleeding heart divided
 Forgive me, forgive me, forgive me

as she describes confession, we feel the pressure of it.  the nervousness as you wait to unload your sins onto a tired old priest.

the bleeding heart refers to the sacred heart of jesus that pricks itself on the crown of thorns surrounding it.  the sacred heart represents mercy.  perhaps it’s “divided” because as a child, sometimes we think that maybe we won’t be forgiven.

the pleading “forgive me,” the begging of validation from a scared and confused child, transformed by the teachings to forgive our neighbor.  but do we really know what it means ?

Vivien’s holding on
 But singing every single word wrong
 On the parade float

children’s recitals are fairly common and celebrated, especially with religious events or story retellings.  perhaps vivien was feeling too pressured, or was taking it as a joke (yet the former is more plausible). after all, she was just a child in a costume.  either way, the performative aspects and being the center of attention tends to create barriers between people of the same faith and even between people and god
Ms. Brown was keeping score
conditioning to compete in righteousness seems to be the centerfold.  while princess diana’s death was a tragedy, it shouldn’t have been used as a game.  she sees this now.

I’d be a believer
 If I thought we had a chance

maybe she would be a believer if she had the chance to delve into faith of her own volition instead of being indoctrinated at a young age, as is customary in families in creating their own “domestic church.”

religions preach a “child-like faith,” in which they’re encouraged to trust blindly and whole-heartedly into the unknown.  but is that really feasible ? is it attainable to preach this concept when it was ingrained into the minds of children before they were sentient ?

this is echoed – maybe she would believe if it was by her own hand.

Lydia wears a cross
 Says she’s never gonna take it off

a big part of christianity is wearing a cross or crucifix.  it’s a means of identifying yourself without saying anything.  lydia, in her innocence and child-like faith (that religions praise so often), says she’ll never take it off.  at that point in her life, she doesn’t want to lose this piece of herself, her relationship with god, or the way that other people see her when the cross beats against her chest.
A technicolour dream coat
Could be a reference to another Andrew Lloyd Webber & Tim Rice musical – Joseph and his Amazing Technicolour Dream Coat.
Listening to Jesus Christ Superstar soundtrack

Jesus Christ Superstar is a controversial 1970 rock opera, and 1971 Broadway production, by Andrew Lloyd Webber and Tim Rice. It presents a modernized (and glamorized) retelling of the weeks before Jesus' crucifixion.



This reference may signal how all-encompassing religion was in Julia’s early years and her appeal toward the more performative aspects of Catholicism.

I’d be a believer
 If it was all just song and dance
many faiths perpetuate harmful rethoric, are hateful and opressive – she’d could belong if religion was based upon love, if it was about joy and forgiveness

Seated in rows
 Knees and eyes closed I felt pretty
 In the shoes and the dress
 Confused by the rest, could he hear me?

julia may be referring to clothes worn during first communion, girls outfits consist of a long, white dress, gloves, and a crownet (these may vary). being in church one can often wonder whether god is really listening and if so, are they able to hear the prayers burried under the splendour, glamorous decor and imagery, the elegant array worn by the priests

annotations: Try not to let go

She repeats “try not to let go”, almost like a mantra.

It’s hard for her to not let go. Here, she’s almost screaming at herself, encouraging herself to keep on holding on to her connections with others and herself – instead of drifting off into chaos, disconnection, isolation.

I need you to believe me when I say I find it hard
 To keep myself from floating away
 I will
 
 [Chorus]
 Try not to let go

She finds herself drifting into herself, which makes it difficult to keep securely connected with the people she has relations with, and perhaps even herself.

Maybe this is happening because of depression or anxiety. She wants the listener to know that it’s not intentional: “I need you to believe me…”

She doesn’t want to be this way. She wants to be connected and tethered. She wants to give love. She just needs some time to figure out how to do this.
Love, love is all that I want now

After everything she’s been through, at this point, all she wants or needs is “love”.

I don’t think this is about love in a romantic relationship, but love in all aspects of her life.

description.plain:
“I Was Neon” is the second single from Julia Jacklin’s third studio album PRE PLEASURE (2022). In contrast with the bobbing art-pop sound of its preceding single “Lydia Wears a Cross”, this track is built around chugging guitars.

Lyrically, it deals with clawing onto oneself while life keeps going forward, using “neon” as a metaphor for those qualities that we might lose as time goes by while desperately wanting to maintain them.

body.plain:
“I Was Neon” is the second single from Julia Jacklin’s third studio album PRE PLEASURE (2022). In contrast with the bobbing art-pop sound of its preceding single “Lydia Wears a Cross”, this track is built around chugging guitars.

Lyrically, it deals with clawing onto oneself while life keeps going forward, using “neon” as a metaphor for those qualities that we might lose as time goes by while desperately wanting to maintain them.

annotations:
I was neon, I was a floodlight
 Arms out reaching for everything in sight
 I swear I could be it, swear I could be it

Neon and floodlights might symbolize who she wants herself to be; positive, happy, welcoming, and outgoing. She is trying to reach out and be welcoming and social toward others, and the last line is her saying that despite feeling like she might be losing what is in her eyes this ideal version of herself, she knew she could be this person again.
[Verse 3]

She continues to reminisce about her past self and what a shining light she was.

She seems to look back at her past self as if she was attuned to the divine flow of life and let it flow through her so readily, and for the good of everything around her.

She was so good. She had so much potential. It’s now lost, but she longs to be that person again.

Am I gonna lose myself again?
 I quite like the person that I am

She questions in almost worried way, if she is going to change again and lose her current self.

She likes who she is right now. Is she going to change again, and for the worse?
Cut wide open, did I let in too much?

Something that happened that shook up her personality.

She says asks if she let in too much, which makes me think that there was some deliberate action of her own.

She was cut wide open: a sudden and violent image. She doesn’t imply that it was a careful and gradual opening up.

It could have, for example, been a psychedelic trip that loosened her mind, opening her up to new ways of processing information. She doesn’t know if she let in too much chaos, which disrupted her previous self-configuration (i.e. the state of her personality at the time).
I was steady, I was soft to the touch

She continues to describe her seemingly pristine prior state.

She was steady, not shaky. She was soft and pleasant, in contrast to rough around the edges.
I swear I could see it, swear I could see it all so clear

She knows with conviction that she had vision at that time. She felt like she knew what she was doing, and where she wanted to go.

She wasn’t lost. She was focused, and she didn’t struggle with existential questions, or life in general, like she does now.

I was neon, I was the nearest door
 I was the sign that said you’ve been here before

She was so together before.

She was bright like a neon light.

She was full of opportunity and potential. Within herself, she could quickly find solace, or whatever she needed next on her quest.

She was a familiar with others. She was inviting and welcoming.

annotations:
Beneath the sheets, you’re just a cave
 A plastic bucket, or a grave

This could reference how the church imposes animalistic connotations on people when having sec. “Beneath the sheets” she’s “just a cave” because she is just a home for someone else’s body to enter in a primal sense. Then a “plastic bucket” again connoting a container to hold the other person, but in a non-tender way. Lastly, she could be seen as a “grave” for the other person with premarital sex or sex outside of conception as a sin. She is leading them to their demise through sexuality.

That put words in my mouth
 All those drinks on the house
This could be a reference to communion wine as a “drink on the house”. Sipping it every Sunday let to the “words in my mouth” or knowledge about sexuality she absorbed from the church.
If I don’t change soon, will it forever eclipse the moon

This is a song about repressing how being taught to repress her sexuality from a very early age by the church confused her teenage self since it coincided with her feeling starting to feel many emotions that were new to her. This line could be referring to the church pushing upon her the belief that what they deem as being sins could have supernatural consequences, like in biblical times. If she doesn’t change and repress this feelings, what will God do about it?
Right when pleasure begins my education creeps in
This perhaps refers to her Catholic upbringing, and the repressive sexual values it prescribed. It intrudes and makes her feel doubt and negativity as soon as she starts to feel pleasure.

description.plain:
“Good Guy” sees Julia Jacklin asking for love from someone for just one night.

In a DIY Magazine interview, Jacklin said this of the song:

“I really love this song, wasn’t sure about putting it on the record because I worried that it was too simple and maybe a bit too submissive. But over time I’ve realised it’s not submissive at all to me; it’s quite the opposite. I guess it’s a song for deep lovers of ‘The Notebook’ who also use Tinder.”

body.plain: At a gig she introduced this song as being about ‘pools and depression’.

annotations: Then you jumped right in
This might be referring to the line in the chorus when Jacklin says that he was “sinking as they swam above”, again using a pool as a metaphor for her dad’s addiction.

Hit me hard when I found height don’t make a man, no
 You grew smaller to me that Saturday when
 You came crashing, crawling down through the back brush

Refers to a common illusion whereby children naively attribute honourable qualities to their parents (and other adults) as they seem grown, tall, “adult”, and capable. This perception shifts as – who is perhaps described as her father – grows smaller in her eyes and in her world as he stumbles through heavily on addiction.

I was shorter than my dad’s dining table
 You were taller than my bedroom door frame

The lyrics play with height, depth, and weight in a beautiful way, demonstrating the complexity of “looking up to” people who “bring you down” as well as “getting high” or having a “sinking feeling.”

These two lines work to place the listener– “I was shorter than my dad’s dining table” implies this was back in the day, in a family home, where the singer may have grown up from youth. “You were taller than my bedroom door frame” also implies the reflection of childhood and growth– now the subject of the lyrics is too tall to be marked on the door frame and has “outgrown” their childhood. Together, these form highly altered perspectives, Alice-in-Wonderland style. This situates the rest of the lines to be interpreted as memories– which are often just as skewed as the idea of one person being shorter than a table while the other was taller than a door frame.
